Copilot caught one real issue and it's a good catch. In the `lofs` loop fix:

```cpp
for (lofs = 1; fragpp[fragmentIndex - lofs] == (uint16_t)-1; lofs++) {
if ((fragmentIndex - lofs) <= 0) { // ← bounds check is AFTER the array access
throw ...
}
}
```

The bounds check runs in the loop *body*, but the out-of-bounds array access `fragpp[fragmentIndex - lofs]` already happened in the loop *condition* on the same iteration. If `fragmentIndex - lofs` goes negative, you read garbage before the guard can fire. Also `<= 0` is wrong — `fragpp[0]` is valid, so the guard should be `< 0`.

Copilot's suggested rewrite is correct:

```cpp
for (lofs = 1;; lofs++) {
```

```cpp
int prevIndex = fragmentIndex - lofs;
if (prevIndex < 0) {
throw BtrieveException(...);
}
if (fragpp[prevIndex] != (uint16_t)-1) {
break;
}
}
```

Check is before the access, threshold is right, logic is identical. Should adopt this. Want me to apply it and push an updated commit to the PR branch?
